results.abstract: rapid growth of Black Sea port Ilyichevsk, which began operating as minor offshoot of Odessa in '58, reflects boom in Soviet trade and rapid expansion of merchant fleet; Ilyichevsk and Odessa provide southern route from USSR to Mediterranean, Atlantic and Indian Oceans and Far East and together have handled more cargo in '70 than any other Soviet port; Govt plans to build 3d port at Grigorevka, which will be bigger than Odessa and Ilyichevsk combined; map

byline.original: By HEDRICK SMITHSpecial to The New York Times

results.lead_paragraph: ILYICHEVSK, U. S. S. R., Nov. 1 -- The Soviet freighter Captain Plaushevsky, bound from Soviet Georgia for Japan with a load of ores and cotton, nosed through the fog and dropped anchor at Ilyichevsk, the fastest-growing port on the Black Sea and now one of the Soviet Union's main gateways to Europe, Africa and Asia.
